* Data Scalability
** Definition
***[#white] ====<size:14>**Data Scalability** is the capability of a system or database to handle an increasing volume of data efficiently without compromising **performance, availability, or data quality.**

** Key Concepts
***[#pink] ====<size:14>Vertical Scaling
****[#yellow] ====<size:14>Increasing the capacity of a single server by adding more resources **(CPU, RAM, storage).**
***[#pink] ====<size:14>Horizontal Scaling
****[#yellow] ====<size:14>Expanding system capabilities by adding more machines to the network.
***[#pink] ====<size:14>Data Partitioning
****[#yellow] ====<size:14>Splitting a dataset into smaller subsets for efficient management and access.
***[#pink] ====<size:14>Data Sharding
****[#yellow] ====<size:14>Distributing data across multiple servers or databases, each responsible for a portion.
***[#pink] ====<size:14>Replication
****[#yellow] ====<size:14>Creating redundant copies of data to ensure high availability and load balancing.
***[#pink] ====<size:14>Distributed Databases
****[#yellow] ====<size:14>Storing data across multiple geographic locations or data centers.
***[#pink] ====<size:14>Cloud Scalability
****[#yellow] ====<size:14>Leveraging cloud services to dynamically allocate and manage resources.

